Alright so an update to this. I have checked the form Japanese TOs can use to gain a license for NON-PROFIT ORGANIZATIONS. 

I have read through this form. I wont translate all of it if, but I will guide you through it in the thread below.

Firstly, Japanese TOs can access this form through a link in Q14/A14. According to Nintendo America this form will be available early November. Nintendo Europe makes no mention of any date. https://t.co/nUs8sNLkyt

On the next page, Nintendo explains that this is the form to apply for a license and asks for your compliance to the guidelines, etc. In bold red letters, it says: "currently, we are not accepting applications for a license for commercial game tournaments". So: only non-profit!! https://t.co/G5apz6CD8h

Under that you can choose what kind of organization your tournament is hosted by. See the second screenshot for a translation of the selectable organizations.

Most Smash TOs will (currently) fall under option 6 "non-profit organizations, public institutions, local governments" https://t.co/TiBGKJ8xUY

Note that if you click on option 2 game stores, option 3 media-related organization, or option 4 commercial/for-profit corporations, it will ask you to return, saying you cannot apply currently. For option 7 influencers, it will refer you to the form "network services". https://t.co/GCNwRzX2gM

Now onto the form itself after having picked option 6 non-profit organizations. First you pick a title. All of them are Switch titles, one of which is Ultimate. As is known already, no Melee. https://t.co/Qm7YzPgVLO

Then
- Is the tournament online/offline?
- Name of the tournament?
- What date will it be held?
- Briefly explain what kind of tournament you're holding?
- What kind of rules are you using? https://t.co/uVNtWs5MFl
In case you are holding a series of the same tournament, how often will you hold them? Relevant for non-profit weeklies, monthlies etc. You can choose up to ten times. https://t.co/0rAAuCPeUe

After agreeing you will comply to the guidelines, you can request a modification of the guidelines. You can ask for:

- An increase in max number of players.
- An increase in entrance fee of participants (explain why),
- and of spectators.
- Something else you want to modify. https://t.co/5PZ5EwxTA7
After this they ask for your personal data, information about your organization and practical information about the tournaments. Name, address, phone number, stuff like that.

Emphasizing this again: as of current, all of this is for NON-PROFIT ORGANIZATIONS. What possibilities and restrictions there are for for-profit organizations? I have no clue, Nintendo has not publicly released any guidelines nor any form for this yet.
